<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Chapter 4 — Language and Meaning
  First full draft.

  Scope:
  - Why language matters for argument evaluation, given Chapters 1–3.
  - Vagueness: terms whose application is unclear at the borders.
  - Ambiguity (lexical and syntactic) and the fallacy of equivocation.
  - Definitions: lexical, stipulative, precising, theoretical, persuasive.
  - Criteria for good definitions; a warning about persuasive definitions.
  - Forward pivot to Chapter 5 (informal fallacies, planned).

  Voice: matter-of-fact, declarative, second-person where it lands,
  politically-current examples where they land, dry humor reserved
  for parentheticals. Continues the "is this any good?" thread by
  showing how language problems can undermine the evaluation work of
  Chapter 3.

  Topic choice rationale: this chapter sits before informal fallacies
  in the planned sequence because some fallacy classifications
  (especially equivocation and persuasive-definition cases) require
  the vocabulary built here.
-->
<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="ch-language-and-meaning">

  <title>Language and Meaning</title>

  <introduction xml:id="ch-language-and-meaning-intro">
    <p>
      So far we have treated statements as if their meanings were
      fixed and obvious. Recognize the argument, reconstruct it,
      check whether the structure is valid or strong: Chapters 1
      through 3 worked at the level of statements arranged into
      premises and conclusions. The internal life of the statements
      themselves — the specific words, the meanings of those words,
      the way meaning can shift between premise and conclusion — has
      been bracketed.
    </p>
    <p>
      It cannot stay bracketed for long. Real arguments are built
      from real words, and real words misbehave. They have edges
      that are unclear. They have more than one meaning. They get
      defined in ways that smuggle in conclusions. An argument
      whose form is impeccable can fail entirely because a word
      shifted between two of its sentences.
    </p>
    <p>
      This chapter is about the words. It builds the vocabulary you
      need to talk about how language can fail us in arguments —
      <term>vagueness</term>, <term>ambiguity</term>, the fallacy of
      <term>equivocation</term> — and it surveys the kinds of
      <term>definitions</term> people offer when language threatens
      to break down. A good argument depends on more than the right
      structure. It depends on words that hold still.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-why-language-matters">
    <title>Why Language Matters for Arguments</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        We met language at the very start of the book, in
        <xref ref="sec-language"/>, when we sorted utterances into
        kinds of speech: stating, asking, commanding, expressing,
        explaining, arguing, and a few more. That work was about the
        <em>functions</em> of language — what we use sentences to do.
        This chapter is about something else. It is about what
        happens inside the sentences themselves, in the choices of
        words and what those words mean.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-why-words-can-betray">
      <title>Words can betray a structurally good argument</title>
      <p>
        The validity of an argument, as we saw in
        <xref ref="ch-evaluating-arguments"/>, depends on its form.
        But form is built out of words, and the same word can carry
        different meanings in different sentences. If a key word in a
        premise means one thing, and the same word in the conclusion
        means another, the form on paper looks fine while the
        argument is in fact going nowhere. Form-level checks won't
        catch this; you need to look inside the words.
      </p>
      <p>
        That is the danger this chapter is about. There are also
        opportunities. A precise definition can fix a vague term and
        let an argument that was previously stuck make real
        progress. A careful translation of an ambiguous sentence can
        clarify which of its readings is meant. The same tools that
        let us notice language problems also let us repair them.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-language-trouble-types">
      <title>Two kinds of trouble</title>
      <p>
        Two categories of language problem account for most of the
        difficulties in everyday and political argument. They are
        worth keeping straight.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Vagueness</alert> is when the application of a term
        is unclear at the borders. The term has a meaning, but the
        meaning shades off rather than ending in a clean line. <q>Tall</q>,
        <q>wealthy</q>, <q>old</q>, <q>reasonable</q>: each picks
        out a real property, but none of them fixes a precise
        threshold. A six-foot-tall person is tall in a kindergarten
        class and short on an NBA roster.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Ambiguity</alert> is when a term has more than one
        distinct meaning, and context does not always settle which
        one is in use. <q>Bank</q> means one thing for rivers and
        another for financial institutions. <q>Free</q> means one
        thing about beer and another about speech. The trouble is
        not borders; it is multiplicities.
      </p>
      <p>
        Vagueness is normal — most natural-language words are vague
        to some degree, and language would be unusable without it.
        Ambiguity is also normal, but it is more surgical in its
        effects on argument. We take them in turn.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-vagueness">
    <title>Vagueness</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        A term is <term>vague</term> when there are clear cases on
        both sides — clear cases where the term applies and clear
        cases where it doesn't — but a range of borderline cases
        where its application is unsettled. Most adjectives in
        natural language are vague in this sense.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <definition xml:id="def-vagueness">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A term is <term>vague</term> when its application is
          unclear at the borders: there are cases where the term
          clearly applies, cases where it clearly does not, and a
          range of borderline cases where reasonable speakers may
          disagree.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-vagueness-ubiquity">
      <title>Vagueness is normal and useful</title>
      <p>
        Almost every adjective and many nouns in natural language
        are vague. <q>Wealthy</q> applies clearly to a billionaire,
        clearly fails for someone with no savings and overdue rent,
        and is genuinely contested in the middle. <q>Adult</q> is
        precise in U.S. law (eighteen and over) but vague in
        contexts like <q>act like an adult</q> or <q>adult
        responsibilities.</q> <q>Reasonable doubt</q> is the
        standard for criminal conviction in the United States, and
        every juror is asked to apply it without anyone able to
        give a numerical threshold.
      </p>
      <p>
        Vagueness is not a flaw in language. A natural language
        without vague terms would be unusable, because an enormous
        amount of useful communication concerns properties whose
        boundaries we have not, and need not, fix. We can point at a
        green leaf and call it green without first agreeing on
        exactly which wavelengths count as green. We can say the
        line is too long without first counting people.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-vagueness-in-argument">
      <title>When vagueness causes argument trouble</title>
      <p>
        Vagueness becomes an argumentative problem when the success
        of an argument turns on exactly where the line is drawn —
        and the line is exactly what the term won't fix.
      </p>
      <p>
        Consider an argument like: <q>The proposed tax applies only
        to the wealthy. Therefore most people will be unaffected.</q>
        On its face, the structure is clear. But the inference works
        only if <q>the wealthy</q> picks out a specific group. If
        <q>wealthy</q> in the proposal means <q>income above two
        hundred thousand dollars</q>, the conclusion holds for most
        people. If it means <q>owns a home</q>, the conclusion is
        much weaker. The argument's strength depends on where the
        vague term is sharpened, and the unsharpened version is
        doing rhetorical work that the sharpened version may not
        sustain.
      </p>
      <p>
        Vague terms in an argument's premises are often a sign that
        the argument needs a <em>precising definition</em> — a
        specific way of fixing the borderline for the purpose of
        this argument. We will come back to those in
        <xref ref="sec-definitions"/>.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-vagueness-vs-controversy">
      <title>Vagueness is not the same as controversy</title>
      <p>
        It is tempting to call any contested term vague. Don't.
        Vagueness is a specific feature: borderline cases where
        application is genuinely unclear. A term can be controversial
        for reasons that have nothing to do with vagueness. <q>Justice</q>
        is contested across centuries of political philosophy not
        because there are borderline cases at the edges of the
        concept but because different theories give substantially
        different accounts of what justice is. <q>Marriage</q> has
        been politically contested over how the term should be used
        — what it should pick out — rather than over borderline cases
        of an agreed concept. These are debates about meaning and
        application, but they are not, in the technical sense,
        debates about vagueness.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-ambiguity">
    <title>Ambiguity and Equivocation</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        A term is <term>ambiguous</term> when it has more than one
        distinct meaning. Ambiguity is a feature of <em>multiplicity</em>,
        not borderlines. The term <q>bank</q> means a financial
        institution and the side of a river; the meanings are
        unrelated. The term <q>light</q> can mean illumination or low
        weight. The term <q>free</q> can mean unconstrained or
        without cost.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <definition xml:id="def-ambiguity">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A term is <term>ambiguous</term> when it has two or more
          distinct meanings, and context does not always settle
          which meaning is in play.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-lexical-vs-syntactic">
      <title>Lexical and syntactic ambiguity</title>
      <p>
        Two kinds of ambiguity are worth distinguishing.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Lexical ambiguity</alert> is when a single word has
        more than one meaning. <q>Bank</q>, <q>light</q>, <q>free</q>,
        <q>fair</q>, <q>right</q>: each is a single word with
        multiple, often unrelated, meanings.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Syntactic ambiguity</alert> (sometimes called
        <em>structural</em> ambiguity) is when a sentence's grammar
        admits more than one parsing. <q>I shot an elephant in my
        pajamas</q> can mean either that the speaker, while wearing
        pajamas, shot an elephant, or that the speaker shot an
        elephant that was wearing the speaker's pajamas. The same
        words; two grammatical structures; two distinct meanings.
        Syntactic ambiguity tends to be funnier than lexical
        ambiguity in everyday life and more dangerous in legal and
        regulatory text, where the grammar of a clause can determine
        what a law actually requires.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-language-equivocation">
      <title>Equivocation</title>
      <p>
        Ambiguity becomes an argumentative problem when a single
        term appears in more than one premise (or in a premise and
        the conclusion) carrying different meanings. The argument
        looks valid because the same word appears in both places,
        but the inference fails because the word means different
        things in each. This is the fallacy of <term>equivocation</term>.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-equivocation-cold-pizza">
        <title>A textbook equivocation</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: Nothing is better than complete happiness.</p>
          <p>P2: Cold pizza is better than nothing.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: Cold pizza is better than complete happiness.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        On the page, this is a hypothetical syllogism — or close to
        one. In reality, it equivocates on <q>nothing</q>. In P1,
        <q>nothing</q> means <q>no thing whatever; there is nothing
        better than complete happiness</q>. In P2, <q>nothing</q>
        means <q>not having anything</q> — in particular, not having
        anything to eat. Different meanings for the same word. The
        argument's structure looks valid because the word appears in
        both premises; the inference fails because the meanings
        don't connect.
      </p>
      <p>
        Real-world equivocations are usually less amusing and harder
        to spot. A politician might argue: <q>The Constitution
        guarantees freedom of speech. So I have the right to say
        whatever I want at this private workplace.</q> The first
        sentence uses <q>freedom of speech</q> in its constitutional
        sense — protection against government restriction. The
        second uses it in a broader sense — freedom from any
        consequence at all. Two meanings; one term; an inference
        that looks straightforward and isn't.
      </p>
      <p>
        Or: <q>Real friends help each other no matter what. So if
        you were a real friend, you'd lie for me.</q> <q>Real
        friend</q> in the first sentence is a description of strong
        loyalty. <q>Real friend</q> in the conclusion smuggles in a
        further commitment — that loyalty includes lying — that the
        first sentence didn't establish. The inference equivocates
        on <q>real friend.</q>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-spotting-equivocation">
      <title>How to spot equivocation</title>
      <p>
        The basic test is to ask, of any term that appears in more
        than one place in an argument, whether it carries the same
        meaning in each appearance. If you can substitute a careful
        gloss for the term in each place, and the glosses turn out
        to be different, the argument equivocates. A good
        reconstruction often reveals equivocation simply by forcing
        you to write each premise out clearly: when you write the
        gloss in place of the term, the argument falls apart and the
        equivocation becomes visible.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-4-3-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Collect ambiguities</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Over the next 24 hours, collect three naturally occurring
          ambiguities — sentences you actually see or hear (on signs,
          in ads, in texts, on social media, in class) where the
          meaning genuinely isn't clear. For each one, identify whether
          the ambiguity is lexical or syntactic, and write out the two
          (or more) possible readings.
        </p>
        <p>
          If any of them appear in the context of an argument, note
          whether the ambiguity could be doing argumentative work —
          that is, whether it might function as an equivocation.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-definitions">
    <title>Definitions and How They Work</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Vagueness and ambiguity are problems. <term>Definitions</term>
        are tools for managing them. A definition fixes the meaning
        of a term — for some purpose, for some audience, in some
        context. Different purposes call for different kinds of
        definitions, and not every definition is doing what it
        appears to be doing.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-kinds-of-definitions">
      <title>Five kinds of definitions</title>
      <p>
        Five kinds of definitions are worth distinguishing for
        purposes of argument analysis. The classification isn't
        perfect — real definitions sometimes do more than one job at
        once — but the categories are useful for noticing what a
        definition is trying to do.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Lexical definitions</alert> report how a term is used
        in some linguistic community. Dictionary definitions are
        paradigmatic. <q><em>Cat</em>: a small domesticated
        carnivorous mammal of the family Felidae.</q> Lexical
        definitions can be true or false: a dictionary entry is
        wrong if the community uses the word differently. They are
        the right kind of definition when the question is <q>what
        does this word mean?</q>
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Stipulative definitions</alert> introduce a new term
        or fix a term's meaning for a particular discussion.
        <q>For purposes of this paper, I will use <em>data center</em>
        to mean any commercial building dedicated primarily to
        computational hardware</q> is stipulative. Stipulative
        definitions are not true or false; they are useful or not.
        They are the right kind of definition when you need a
        precise term for a discussion and an existing one is too
        loose, too overloaded, or absent.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Precising definitions</alert> sharpen a vague term in
        a way that respects ordinary usage but adds enough precision
        to settle a disputed application. <q><em>Reasonable doubt</em>
        in this jurisdiction is to be interpreted as the level of
        certainty a reasonable person would require before making an
        important personal decision</q> is precising. Precising
        definitions matter most when an argument hinges on a vague
        term and the parties to the argument need to agree on where
        the line falls.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Theoretical definitions</alert> embed a term in a
        scientific or theoretical framework. <q><em>Mass</em> is the
        coefficient relating force and acceleration in
        <m>F = ma</m>.</q> Theoretical definitions are answerable to
        the framework — if the framework changes, the definition may
        change with it. They are the right kind of definition when
        the term is part of a structured account of how something
        works.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Persuasive definitions</alert> smuggle evaluation into
        what looks like a neutral definition. <q><em>Patriotism</em>
        is supporting our troops without question.</q> <q><em>Real
        equality</em> means treating everyone identically regardless
        of context.</q> A persuasive definition does not just report
        usage or sharpen a term; it builds a substantive position
        into the meaning of the word, so that anyone using the term
        is silently endorsing that position. Persuasive definitions
        are the dangerous kind. They are the form most likely to
        produce arguments whose structure looks fine while the
        crucial work happens off-stage, in the loaded definition.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-good-definitions">
      <title>Criteria for good definitions</title>
      <p>
        Not all definitions are equally good. The classical criteria
        for a good lexical or precising definition are worth keeping
        in mind:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Not too broad.</alert> The definition should not
            include things that don't fit. Defining <em>cat</em> as
            <q>any small mammal</q> is too broad: rabbits and squirrels
            would qualify.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Not too narrow.</alert> The definition should not
            exclude things that do fit. Defining <em>cat</em> as
            <q>a domesticated short-haired Felidae</q> is too narrow:
            long-haired domesticated cats and undomesticated species
            are excluded.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Not circular.</alert> The definition should not
            use the term being defined. <q><em>Logic</em> is the
            study of logical reasoning</q> tells the reader nothing.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Not in obscure or figurative language.</alert>
            Definitions are supposed to clarify. If the definition
            is harder to understand than the term, something has
            gone wrong.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Affirmative when possible.</alert> Telling someone
            what a thing is, rather than what it isn't, is usually
            more useful. Some terms (<q>colorblind</q>, <q>orphan</q>)
            naturally take negative definitions, but the default is
            to say what the thing is.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Persuasive definitions usually fail at least one of the
        first three criteria — a persuasive definition of <em>patriotism</em>
        is likely to be too narrow (excluding kinds of love of
        country the definer dislikes) or to import controversial
        content as if it were neutral. Spotting where a definition
        is doing its sneaky work is often a matter of asking which
        of these criteria it fails.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-genus-and-difference">
      <title>Definition by genus and difference</title>
      <p>
        The classical method for constructing a definition, going
        back to Aristotle, is <term>definition by genus and difference</term>.
        Identify a broader category (the <em>genus</em>) that
        contains the thing being defined, and then specify the
        feature or features that distinguish the thing from other
        members of the genus (the <em>difference</em>). <q><em>Cat</em>:
        a small carnivorous mammal (genus: small carnivorous mammals)
        of the family Felidae (difference: belonging to Felidae).</q>
        <q><em>Triangle</em>: a polygon (genus) with exactly three
        sides (difference).</q>
      </p>
      <p>
        Genus and difference is not the only good way to define a
        term, but it is a reliable starting point. When a definition
        feels evasive or off, asking <q>what is the genus and what
        is the difference?</q> often reveals the trouble.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-4-4-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Evaluate a real definition</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a definition in actual use — a legal definition, a
          policy document, a dictionary entry, a terms-of-service
          agreement, a course syllabus, a campus policy. Classify it
          (stipulative, lexical, precising, theoretical, or
          persuasive). Then evaluate it using the criteria from this
          section: Is it too broad? Too narrow? Circular? Negative
          when it doesn't need to be?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-where-headed-ch4">
    <title>Where We're Headed</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Vagueness, ambiguity, equivocation, and definitions:
        Chapter 4 has been a tour of the ways language can shape,
        and undermine, the arguments built from it.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-where-headed-ch4-summary">
      <title>What this chapter gave us</title>
      <p>
        We can now see that argument evaluation has another layer
        beyond what Chapter 3 covered. Validity tells us about the
        relation between premises and conclusion. But the truth and
        the meaning of the premises themselves depend on words, and
        words can be vague, ambiguous, or defined in ways that bias
        the argument. An argument can pass the structural tests of
        Chapter 3 and still fail because of language trouble. The
        question <em>is this argument any good?</em> now has another
        front: are the words holding still?
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-where-headed-ch4-pivot">
      <title>What's coming</title>
      <p>
        The next chapter introduces the family of <term>informal
        fallacies</term> — patterns of bad reasoning that recur
        often enough to have names. Some of those fallacies are
        language-based (equivocation, which we have already met,
        plus relatives like the fallacy of accent and a few others),
        and the vocabulary of this chapter feeds directly into them.
        Others are about the relation between premises and
        conclusions in subtler ways than validity captures.
      </p>
      <p>
        After the fallacies chapter, the book turns to the formal
        machinery: categorical logic in Part II, sentential logic in
        Part III, statistical reasoning in Part IV. Each of those
        domains will give us procedures for evaluating arguments
        more rigorously than the hand-classification of forms we
        have done so far. The language tools of this chapter will
        keep mattering throughout — formal machinery cannot save an
        argument whose key term equivocates.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <conclusion xml:id="conclusion-ch4">
    <title>Chapter Summary</title>

    <p>
      This chapter treated language as part of argument evaluation. The
      core ideas, section by section:
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Why Language Matters for Arguments (§4.1).</alert>
      Structurally good reasoning can still go wrong when the language
      in the premises or conclusion is unclear. Vagueness, ambiguity,
      and bad definitions can hide the actual issue, shift the argument,
      or make a conclusion seem better supported than it is.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Vagueness (§4.2).</alert> A vague term has borderline
      cases. Vagueness is normal and often useful, but it becomes a
      problem when an argument depends on a boundary that the arguer has
      not made clear.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Ambiguity and Equivocation (§4.3).</alert> An ambiguous
      expression has more than one meaning. Lexical ambiguity involves
      words or phrases with multiple meanings; syntactic ambiguity
      involves sentence structure. Equivocation occurs when an argument
      shifts between meanings and makes the inference look stronger than
      it is.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Definitions and How They Work (§4.4).</alert> Definitions
      can report usage, stipulate a meaning, clarify a term, recommend a
      way of speaking, or persuade. Good definitions fit their purpose,
      avoid circularity, and mark the relevant boundaries clearly enough
      for the argument at hand.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Where We're Headed (§4.5).</alert> The language skills in
      this chapter prepare us for informal fallacies, especially
      equivocation and persuasive definitions. Chapter 5 uses these
      tools while keeping Chapter 4 optional for adopters who skip it.
    </p>

  </conclusion>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch4-key-terms">
    <title>Key Terms</title>

    <p>Listed alphabetically, with section references.</p>

    <dl>
      <li xml:id="term-ch4-ambiguity">
        <title>Ambiguity</title>
        <p>A feature of language in which an expression has more than one meaning. (§4.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch4-definition-by-genus-difference">
        <title>Definition by genus and difference</title>
        <p>A definition that places something in a general class and then states what distinguishes it from other members of that class. (§4.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch4-equivocation">
        <title>Equivocation</title>
        <p>A shift in meaning within an argument that makes the reasoning look stronger than it is. (§4.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch4-lexical-ambiguity">
        <title>Lexical ambiguity</title>
        <p>Ambiguity that comes from a word or phrase having more than one meaning. (§4.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch4-persuasive-definition">
        <title>Persuasive definition</title>
        <p>A definition that tries to influence attitudes toward what is being defined, not merely report or clarify usage. (§4.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch4-stipulative-definition">
        <title>Stipulative definition</title>
        <p>A definition that assigns a meaning to a term for a particular context or discussion. (§4.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch4-syntactic-ambiguity">
        <title>Syntactic ambiguity</title>
        <p>Ambiguity that comes from the structure or grammar of a sentence. (§4.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch4-vagueness">
        <title>Vagueness</title>
        <p>A feature of language in which a term has borderline cases. (§4.2)</p>
      </li>
    </dl>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch4">
    <title>End-of-Chapter Exercises</title>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch4-s01">
      <title>Exercise Set 1: Identifying Vague Terms</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each sentence, identify any vague term and explain
          briefly why it is vague. If the sentence is part of an
          argument, note whether the vagueness is doing
          argumentative work.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s01-01">
        <statement>
          <p>The new policy will only affect wealthy households.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s01-02">
        <statement>
          <p>The defendant should be acquitted because there is reasonable doubt.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s01-03">
        <statement>
          <p>This product contains only natural ingredients.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s01-04">
        <statement>
          <p>The water in the kettle is now hot.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch4-s02">
      <title>Exercise Set 2: Ambiguity (Lexical and Syntactic)</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each sentence, identify whether it is ambiguous; if
          so, explain whether the ambiguity is lexical or syntactic
          and give the two readings.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s02-01">
        <statement>
          <p>I went to the bank yesterday.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s02-02">
        <statement>
          <p>Visiting relatives can be exhausting.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s02-03">
        <statement>
          <p>The chicken is ready to eat.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s02-04">
        <statement>
          <p>You have the right to remain silent.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch4-s03">
      <title>Exercise Set 3: Spotting Equivocation</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Each of the following arguments equivocates on a term.
          Identify the term, explain the two meanings, and say where
          the inference fails.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s03-01">
        <statement>
          <p>The end of life is death. The end of life is what gives life its meaning. So death is what gives life its meaning.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s03-02">
        <statement>
          <p>The Constitution protects free speech. Banning a speaker from this private platform is an attack on free speech. So the Constitution prohibits the platform from banning the speaker.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s03-03">
        <statement>
          <p>All laws can be broken. The law of gravity is a law. So the law of gravity can be broken.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch4-s04">
      <title>Exercise Set 4: Classifying Definitions</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each definition below, classify it as lexical,
          stipulative, precising, theoretical, or persuasive.
          Briefly justify your classification.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s04-01">
        <statement>
          <p><q>For the purposes of this study, a <em>frequent visitor</em> is anyone who has visited the website at least three times in the past month.</q></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s04-02">
        <statement>
          <p><q><em>Common sense</em> is the kind of judgment that any sensible person would agree with.</q></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s04-03">
        <statement>
          <p><q>True freedom is the freedom to live by traditional values without interference from government bureaucrats.</q></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s04-04">
        <statement>
          <p><q><em>Velocity</em> is the rate of change of position with respect to time.</q></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch4-s05">
      <title>Exercise Set 5: Critiquing Definitions</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Each of the following definitions fails one or more of the
          standard criteria for a good definition. Identify which
          criterion or criteria the definition fails, and explain.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s05-01">
        <statement>
          <p><q><em>Logic</em> is the study of how to reason logically.</q></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s05-02">
        <statement>
          <p><q><em>Chair</em>: a piece of furniture.</q></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s05-03">
        <statement>
          <p><q><em>Cat</em>: a four-legged carnivorous mammal that is not a dog.</q></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s05-04">
        <statement>
          <p><q><em>Justice</em> is the harmonious arrangement of the soul that mirrors the harmonious arrangement of the well-ordered city.</q></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch4-s06">
      <title>Exercise Set 6: Mixed Application</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each passage, identify whatever language problems are
          present (vagueness, ambiguity, equivocation, persuasive
          definition) and briefly explain how each problem affects
          the argument.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s06-01">
        <statement>
          <p>Real environmentalists support nuclear power because nuclear power is the only large-scale low-carbon energy source. Senator X opposes nuclear power. So Senator X is not a real environmentalist.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s06-02">
        <statement>
          <p>The administration says it values academic freedom. Academic freedom means professors can teach what they want. So the administration should not have any curriculum requirements.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-s06-03">
        <statement>
          <p>Healthy foods are foods that don't contain artificial ingredients. So organic candy is healthy.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch4-writing">
      <title>Writing Prompt</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          This prompt connects to the field exercises in this chapter.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch4-writing-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Choose one of the ambiguities you collected in Field
            Exercise 4-1 or the definition you evaluated in Field
            Exercise 4-2. Write a short analysis.
          </p>
          <p>
            If you are working with an ambiguity: explain why the
            ambiguity exists, whether it matters in context, and how
            you would resolve it.
          </p>
          <p>
            If you are working with a definition: explain what the
            definition does well and what it does poorly, and propose
            a revision if you think it needs one.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</chapter>
